{
  "texts": [
    "Based on a predetermined probability, a crossover may occur, or the parents are directly copied to the children population.",
    "This strategy ensures the preservation of superior-quality solutions.If crossover happens, each of the 6 numbers can be swapped between two parents with a probability of 50%.The fitness functions and the way they are calculated are defined in the next subsection.",
    "Fitness FunctionsWe use the same fitness functions for both case studies: execution time and diversity.",
    "The reason for selecting execution time as a fitness function is that execution time provides a quantifiable and direct measure of system performance, particularly in scenarios demanding maximum computational resources.",
    "By optimizing for the longest execution time, we aim to uncover the upper limits of system performance, thus directly aligning with the goals of WCET analysis.Relying exclusively on execution time as a fitness function can result in the exploration of only a limited subset of the input space."
  ]
}